## 3. Understandable

### 3.1 Readable

- MUST (SC 3.1.1 ‚Äî Language of Page): The `<html>` element must have a valid `lang` attribute matching the content language. Update dynamically when the user switches locale via `LanguageContext`.
- SHOULD (SC 3.1.2 ‚Äî Language of Parts): Inline content in a different language (e.g., Hindi enrollment steps) must use the `lang` attribute on the containing element.

### 3.2 Predictable

- MUST (SC 3.2.1 ‚Äî On Focus): Focusing an element must not trigger a context change (no navigation, no form submission, no modal opening on focus alone).
- MUST (SC 3.2.2 ‚Äî On Input): Changing a form control value must not automatically trigger unexpected context changes unless the user is informed beforehand.
- MUST (SC 3.2.3 ‚Äî Consistent Navigation): Sidebar navigation order and structure must remain consistent across all pages. Never reorder nav items based on context.
- MUST (SC 3.2.6 ‚Äî Consistent Help): If a help mechanism is provided (help icon, documentation link, support contact), it must appear in the same relative position on every page.

### 3.3 Input Assistance

- MUST (SC 3.3.1 ‚Äî Error Identification): Form validation errors must be identified in text, associated with the relevant field, and not rely solely on color.
- MUST (SC 3.3.2 ‚Äî Labels or Instructions): Every input has a visible, persistent label. Required fields are indicated.
- MUST (SC 3.3.3 ‚Äî Error Suggestion): When an input error is detected and a correction is known, suggest the correction to the user.
- MUST (SC 3.3.4 ‚Äî Error Prevention): Destructive actions (device wipe, unenroll, delete profile/group/geofence) MUST use a confirmation dialog (Radix `AlertDialog`). Never use `window.confirm()` ‚Äî it is inaccessible to screen readers, visually inconsistent, and blocks the main thread.
- MUST (SC 3.3.7 ‚Äî Redundant Entry): Do not require users to re-enter information they have already provided in the same session unless re-confirmation is required for security.
- MUST (SC 3.3.8 ‚Äî Accessible Authentication, Minimum): Authentication flows must not require cognitive function tests (e.g., CAPTCHA puzzles, memorizing passwords without paste support). Allow password managers, biometrics, and passkeys.

---

## 4. Robust

### 4.1 Compatible

- MUST (SC 4.1.2 ‚Äî Name, Role, Value): All interactive components expose correct name, role, and state to assistive technology. Specifically:
  - `aria-expanded` must reflect actual collapsed/expanded state dynamically. Never hardcode `aria-expanded="true"`.
  - `aria-selected` on tab-like elements must reflect actual selection.
  - `aria-current="page"` on the active sidebar navigation link.
  - Custom components built with Radix primitives must preserve their built-in ARIA semantics.
- MUST (SC 4.1.3 ‚Äî Status Messages): Dynamic content updates that don't receive focus must be announced via ARIA live regions.
  - Stat card value changes: use `role="status"` or `aria-live="polite"`.
  - Toast notifications: ensure the toast container has `aria-live="polite"` and `role="status"`.
  - Table loading/error states: announce via `aria-live="polite"`.
  - Form submission success/failure: announce results without moving focus.

---

## General Enforcement Rules

- When modifying any file, audit adjacent code for WCAG violations listed above. Fix violations in the same changeset when effort is low.
- Every new interactive component must pass a keyboard-only navigation test before merge.
- Every new color combination must be verified against WCAG AA contrast thresholds before use.
- All animations must include a `prefers-reduced-motion` fallback.
- Never suppress or remove existing accessibility features (skip link, aria labels, sr-only tables, high contrast mode, reduced motion support) without explicit justification.
